  "prompt": "Define melting point and boiling point? What is the difference?",
  "response": "**Melting Point** and **Boiling Point** are both physical properties of substances that describe the temperature at which phase changes occur. Here's a detailed definition of each and the key differences between them:\n\n---\n\n### **Melting Point**:\n- The melting point is the temperature at which a solid substance transitions into a liquid state.\n- At this temperature, the solid and liquid phases of the substance coexist in equilibrium.\n- It is a characteristic property of a substance and is often used to identify or characterize materials.\n- Example: The melting point of ice (solid water) is **0\u00b0C (32\u00b0F)** at standard atmospheric pressure.\n\n---\n\n### **Boiling Point**:\n- The boiling point is the temperature at which a liquid substance transitions into a gaseous state (vapor).\n- At this temperature, the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the external pressure (usually atmospheric pressure).\n- Like the melting point, the boiling point is also a characteristic property of a substance.\n- Example: The boiling point of water is **100\u00b0C (212\u00b0F)** at standard atmospheric pressure.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Differences**:\n\n| **Aspect**               | **Melting Point**                            | **Boiling Point**                            |\n|--------------------------|---------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|\n| **Phase Change**         | Solid \u2192 Liquid                              | Liquid \u2192 Gas                                |\n| **Energy Required**      | Overcomes forces holding the solid together | Overcomes forces holding the liquid together and provides energy for vaporization |\n| **Pressure Dependence**  | Less sensitive to external pressure         | Highly dependent on external pressure       |\n| **Example**              | Melting of ice at 0\u00b0C                       | Boiling of water at 100\u00b0C                   |\n\n---\n\n### **Summary**:\nThe melting point is the temperature at which a solid turns into a liquid, while the boiling point is the temperature at which a liquid turns into a gas. Both are intrinsic properties of a substance but describe different phase transitions.",
